ize     = \n| transmission     = [[Diesel electric]]\n| multipleworking  = Yes\n| maxspeed         = {{convert|100|km/h|0|abbr=on}}\n| poweroutput      = {{convert|4,500|hp|kW|abbr=on}}\n| tractiveeffort   = Starting: {{convert|544|kN|0|abbr=on}} <!-- {{convert||t lbf|abbr=on}} -->\nContinuous: 405 kN\n| factorofadhesion = \n| trainheating     = \n| locobrakes       = \n| locobrakeforce   = \n| trainbrakes      = [[Railway air brake|Air]], [[Dynamic braking|Dynamic Brake]]\n| safety           = \n| operator         = [[Indian Railways]]\n| operatorclass    = \n| powerclass       = \n| numinclass       = \n| fleetnumbers     = '''49001+'''\n| officialname     = \n| nicknames        = \n| axleloadclass    = \n| locale           = [[Roza]] ([[Uttar Pradesh]]), [[Gandhidham]] ([[Gujarat]])\n| deliverydate     = 12 October 2017\n| firstrundate     = \n| lastrundate      = \n| retiredate       = \n| withdrawndate    = \n| preservedunits   = \n| restoredate      = \n| scrapdate        = \n| currentowner     = \n| disposition      = \n}}\n\nThe '''WDG-4G''' ('''W'''[[5 ft 6 in gauge railway|ide/broad Gauge]] '''D'''[[Diesel locomotive|iesel]] '''G'''[[rail freight transport|oods/freight]], Class '''4G''') is a class of 4,500 HP [[Diesel locomotive|Diesel-electric]] freight [[locomotive]] developed by [[GE Transportation]] based on its existing [[GE Evolution series|Evolution Series]] of locomotives for [[Indian Railways]]. The locomotives will be manufactured in a newly constructed factory ([[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra]]) in [[Bihar]].  They will be used exclusively for freight hauling and will replace the existing fleet of old [[American Locomotive Company|Alco]] locomotives. They will also feature the most fuel efficient diesel engine ([[GE GEVO|GEVO]]) used till now by Indian Railways. For driver's comfort, cabs will have air conditioning and toilets.<ref>{{cite web|title=GE report on Indian deal|url=https://www.ge.com/reports/ge-signs-2-6-billion-deal-supply-1000-locomotives-indias-vast-railway-network/}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nThe development of WDG-4G loco can be traced back to September 2013, when the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]] had received bids from six global firms: [[Siemens]], [[Alstom]], [[Bombardier Transportation|Bombardier]], [[General Electric]], [[CSR Corporation Limited|CSR Corp]] and CNR Corp.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/economy/logistics/chinese-firms-join-race-to-supply-locos-to-railways/article5207350.ece|title=Chinese firms join race to supply locos to Railways|first=Mamuni|last=Das|date=6 October 2013|publisher=}}</ref> However, [[Indian Railways]] rejected the bid of both Chinese firms ([[CSR Corporation Limited|CSR]] and CNR) for the two giant manufacturing projects in [[Bihar]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Railways-denies-Chinese-firms-locomotive-manufacturing-projects-for-non-compliance/articleshow/24621682.cms |title=Railways denies Chinese firms\u2019 locomotive manufacturing projects for non-compliance |date=2013-10-24 |website=timesofindia.indiatimes.com |access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, the [[Union Council of Ministers|Union Cabinet]] gave its approval for setting up [[Electric Locomotive Factory Madhepura|Electric Locomotive Factory]] in [[Madhepura district|Madhepura]] and Diesel Locomotive Factory (DLF) in Marhowra at an approximate cost of {{INRConvert|1293.57|c}} and {{INRConvert|2052.58|c}} respectively.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=102635 |title=Setting up of electric locomotive factory at Madhepura and Diesel locomotive factory at Marhowra, Bihar  |date=2014-01-20 |website=pib.nic.in |access-date=2017-12-14}}</ref>\n\nOn 9 November 2015, the [[Ministry of Railways (India)|Ministry of Railways]] awarded the contracts for [[Madhepura district|Madhepura]] project and [[Marhaura|Marhowra]] project to [[Alstom]] and General Electric respectively in a collective amount of US$6 billion. This multi crore rupees deal was seen as the country's first FDI in the railway sector.<ref>{{cite web|title=Setting up of electric locomotive factory at Madhepura and Diesel locomotive factory at Marhowra, Bihar|url=http://pib.nic.in/newsite/PrintRelease.aspx?relid=102635|publisher=Indian Railways}}</ref>\nAfter winning the contract, [[General Electric]] started the designing of locomotives.They were designed by the Indian branch of GE Global Research in Bangalore.Both the locomotives are based on GE's Evolution-series locomotives, which are one of the most fuel efficient and least emissions making locomotives in the world.To meet specific local requirements, the locomotive had to weigh only 22 tons per axle, while its American counterparts typically weigh 25 to 30 tons.GE faced a challenge to take out as much as 48 tons from the whole locomotive.<ref>{{cite web|title=The heaviest haul:GE|url=https://www.ge.com/reports/heaviest-haul-locomotives-putting-indian-state-fast-track/}}</ref>\n\nThe first locomotive rolled out GE's Erie plant on 3 August 2017 with the orange and yellow paint livery.<ref>{{cite web|title=GE reveals Indian Railways Evolution locomotive livery|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/traction-rolling-stock/single-view/view/ge-reveals-indian-railways-evolution-locomotive-livery.html|publisher=Railway Gazette}}</ref>\n\nGeneral Electric's first diesel locomotive arrived in India on October 11, 2017 from the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/business/companies/marhowra-deal-general-electrics-first-diesel-loco-arrives-in-india-4885938/|title=Marhowra deal: General Electric\u2019s first diesel loco arrives in India|date=12 October 2017|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=vote.us.org|url=https://vote.us.org/memo/thread/15317/infrastructure-boost-indian-railways-set-to-get-modern-\u2018make-in-india\u2019-loco/}}</ref>\n\n==Production==\nAccording to the contract, first 100 locomotives to be imported or assembled using imported kits and the rest 900 be built in India with 70% Indian content. The locomotives will be built at [[Diesel Locomotive Factory, Marhowra]] in [[Bihar]] which is a joint venture between [[Indian Railways]] and [[General Electric]] with the former owning 26% stake and later owning rest 74%. The plant is expected to be operational from the first quarter of 2018.<ref name=\"India receives first GE locomotive\">{{cite web|title=India receives first GE locomotive|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/india-receives-first-ge-locomotive-under-2-5-billion-deal/articleshow/61035592.cms|publisher=Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nThe plant will produce 100 locomotives per year for 10 years from 2019. The railways will be paying a cost of Rs146\u00b76bn for 1,000 locomotives. GE would maintain the locomotives until the 13th year of the contract, at which point Indian Railways would take over responsibility for maintenance.<ref>{{cite web|title=GE wins 1000 locomotive contract|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/ge-wins-1000-locomotive-indian-railways-deal.html}}</ref>\n\n==Loco Shed Holding WDG-4G==\n* '''Diesel Loco Shed Roza''' -182<br />'''Total active locomotives in Service as of 01-04-2020:''' 182<br />('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)<br />'''Source:''' http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,541,710,717\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India}}\n\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of India]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian diesel locomotive class}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{