motive Factory, Marhowra]] in [[Bihar]] which is a joint venture between [[Indian Railways]] and [[General Electric]] with the former owning 26% stake and later owning rest 74%. The plant is expected to be operational from the first quarter of 2018.<ref name=\"India receives first GE locomotive\">{{cite web|title=India receives first GE locomotive|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/transportation/railways/india-receives-first-ge-locomotive-under-2-5-billion-deal/articleshow/61035592.cms|publisher=Economic Times}}</ref>\n\nThe plant will produce 100 locomotives per year for 10 years from 2019. The railways will be paying a cost of Rs146\u00b76bn for 1,000 locomotives. GE would maintain the locomotives until the 13th year of the contract, at which point Indian Railways would take over responsibility for maintenance.<ref>{{cite web|title=GE wins 1000 locomotive contract|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/business/single-view/view/ge-wins-1000-locomotive-indian-railways-deal.html}}</ref>\n\n==Loco Shed Holding WDG-4G==\n* '''Diesel Loco Shed Roza''' -182<br />Total active locomotives in Service as of 01-04-2020: 182<br />('''Note-'''Before updating the information here anybody should check out the railways current official data first in the  '''Source''' link then change the data.)<br />'''Source:''' http://www.indianrailways.gov.in/railwayboard/view_section.jsp?lang=0&id=0,1,304,366,541,710,717\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Broad gauge locomotives of India}}\n\n[[Category:Diesel-electric locomotives of India]]\n", "name_user": "Suvadeep Saha56", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLoco Shed Holding WDG-4G:minor edit.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_locomotives_class_WDG-4G"}
{"title_page": "Yuga", "text_new": "{{About||the 2006 '''film'''|Yuga (film)}}\n{{short description|Epoch or era in a four age cycle in Hinduism}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n\n[[File:Four Yugas of Hindu Eschatology.svg|thumb|368x368px|The Four Yugas in one cycle according to some modern scholars, Hindu Cosmology]]\n\nA '''Yuga''' in [[Hinduism]] is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. There are a total of four Yugas: ''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''. The four Yugas differ in duration, virtues, etc. where Satya Yuga has the most, Treta Yuga the 2<sup>nd</sup> most, Dvapara the 3<sup>rd</sup> most, and Kali Yuga the least.\n\nA '''Mahayuga''' or '''Chaturyuga''' (also an epoch) is a cycle of the Yugas which can be followed by another Mahayuga of the same duration. Each Mahayuga consists of a descending set of the four Yugas where one Mahayuga ends with Kali Yuga and another starts with Satya Yuga (S,T,D,K) (S,T,D,K).\n\nSome modern scholars believe in a Mahayuga consisting of a much shorter descending and ascending set of the four Yugas where each Mahayuga starts and ends with Satya Yuga and has two Kali Yugas occuring in the middle (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S) (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S). \n\nAccording to the epic [[Mahabharata]], the current age is Kali Yuga which started in 3102 BCE after [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]] left this world. (See [[Kali Yuga]]). Examining each yuga's characteristics, one can easily see that the current age is Kali Yuga.\n\nSome modern scholars say that our present time is ascending Kali Yuga,<ref>{{cite book| url = https://books.google.com/?id=BBwLVlOipyUC&pg=PA15&dq=four+yugas#v=onepage&q=four%20yugas&f=false| title=The Path to Immortality|page=15|first1= Mark L.|last1=Prophet|first2=Elizabeth|last2=Clare Prophet|author2-link=Elizabeth Clare Prophet|publisher= Summit University Press| isbn=9781932890099| year=2006}}</ref> while some other scholars say that Kali Yuga ended in 1700 CE and now we're in ascending Dwapara Yuga.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Holy Science|last=Swami|first=Sri Yukeshwar Giri|publisher=Yogoda Satsang Society|year=1949|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics of the four Yugas ==\nThere are four Yugas:\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]'' (or Krita Yuga)\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\n* ''[[Dwapara Yuga]]''\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\n\n=== Characteristics of each Yuga ===\n\n* '''Satya Yuga''' (\"The age of truth\" or \"[[Golden Age#Hindu|Golden Age]]\"): The first and best yuga. It was the age of truth and perfection. This yuga had no crimes and all humans were kind and friendly. The Krita Yuga was so named because there was but one religion, and all men were saintly: therefore they were not required to perform religious ceremonies. Humans were long lived, powerfully built, honest, youthful, vigorous, erudite and virtuous. The Vedas were one. All mankind could attain to supreme blessedness. There was no agriculture or mining as the earth yielded those riches on its own. Weather was pleasant and everyone was happy. There were no religious sects. There was no disease, decrepitude or fear of anything.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n* '''Treta Yuga''': This is the second yuga in order. However, \"treta\" means the \"third\". In this age, virtue diminishes slightly. At the beginning of the age, many emperors rise to dominance and conquer the world. Wars become frequent and weather begins to change to extremities. People become slightly diminished compared to their predecessors. Agriculture, labour and mining become existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n* '''Dvapara Yuga''': This is the third yuga in order. However, \"dvapara\" means \"two\". In this age, people become tainted with qualities and aren't as strong as their ancestors. Diseases become rampant. Humans are discontent and fight each other. Vedas are divided into four parts. People still possess characteristics of youth in old age. Average lifespan of humans is around a few centuries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''Kal Yuga''': The final age. It is the age of darkness and ignorance. People stop following [[Dharma]] and lack virtue. They become slaves to their passions and are barely as powerful as their earliest ancestors in the Satya Yuga. Society falls into disuse and people become liars and hypocrites. Knowledge is lost and scriptures are diminished. Humans eat forbidden and dirty food. The environment is polluted, water and food become scarce. Wealth is heavily diminished. Families become non-existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==The Traditional cycle of Yugas==\n[[File:Time Units in Hindu Cosmology.png|frame|Relationship between various time units in Hindu cosmology]]\n\nThe traditional cycle of the Yugas has been mentioned in the [[Mahabharata]] and it is widely accepted since ancient times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} The 4th century indian mathematician [[Aryabhata]] calculated the beginning of Kali Yuga.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nEach cycle of a Mahayuga repeats the four Yugas (ages) in the following order: Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali.<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 12.2.39 (yugas order)|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|text=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.|source=[https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/ Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a 12.2.39]}}\n\n'''(For all the below numbers, see [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]]).'''\n\n* Satya Yuga\u20141,728,000 years (4800 divine)\n* Treta Yuga\u20141,296,000 years (3600 divine)\n* Dvapara Yuga\u2014864,000 years (2400 divine)\n* Kali Yuga\u2014432,000 years (1200 divine)\n\nWith one traditional Mahayuga cycle containing a set of descending yugas, it lasts for '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''. This differs greatly from the modern cycle's '''24,000 years'''.\n\nTo calculate the lifespan of the universe or Brahma using the Mahayuga duration, see the \"Current Date\" section of [[Hindu units of time]].\n\n==The Modern cycle of Yugas==\n\nA shorter calculation is promoted <ref>{{Citation|last=Sadhguru|title=The Great Cycles or 'YUGAS' Isha Fondation Sadhguru|date=2017-09-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaHVNQwO68E|volume=|pages=|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> by modern day spiritual leaders such as [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]] giving the approximate length of yugas as:\n\n* Satya Yuga\u20144800 years\n* Treta Yuga\u20143600 years\n* Dvapara Yuga\u20142400 years\n* Kali Yuga\u20141200 years\n\nWith one modern Mahayuga cycle containing a set of descending and ascending yugas{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}, it lasts for '''24,000 years'''. This differs greatly from the traditional cycle's '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''.\n\nSome other scholars{{Who|date=April 2020}} believe in a 25,772 year cycle because it coincides with [[axial precession]], [[Astronomical precession]] and another planetary body ([[Planet Nine]]) that influences our solar system.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} {{Original research|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe common belief until Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri had analyzed the dating of the Yuga cycles was that the Kali Yuga would last for roughly 432,000 years after the end of the Dwapara Yuga (3102 BCE).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} It's believed that this originated during the puranic times when the famous astronomer Aryabhatta recalculated the timeline by artificially inflating the traditional 12,000 year figure with a multiplication of 360, which was represented as the number of \"human years\" that make up a single \"divine year\".{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} It is believed that this was likely a purposeful miscalculation due to conflicts with one of the preeminent astronomer of the time [[Brahmagupta]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nHowever, both the Mahabharata (which was used by Aryabhatta in his calculations) and the Manu Smriti have the original value of 12,000 years for one half of the Yuga cycle.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAccording to one Puranic astronomical estimate, the four Yuga have the following durations:<ref name=\"penprase182\" />\n\n*Satya Yuga equals 1,728,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|page=50|first=Hans|last=Kng|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826494238|date=2006-10-31}}</ref>\n*Treta Yuga equals 1,296,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Dvapara Yuga equals 864,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Kali Yuga equals 432,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nTogether, these four yuga constitute one Mahayuga, equal to 4.32 million human years.<ref name=penprase182>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|first=Bryan E.|last=Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> According to one version, there are 1,000 Mahayugas in one day of [[Brahma]] or 4.32 billion human years. A Mahakalpa consists of 100 years of Brahma.<ref name=penprase182/>\n\nAccording to [[Srimad Bhagavatam]] 3.11.19, which most scholars agree was composed around Mahabharat war (3000 to 3100 BCE){{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}, the Yugas are much longer, using a divine year in which one day is equal to one human year, thus:\n\n{{cquote|one year of [[Deva (Hinduism)|divine beings]] is equal to 360 years of the human beings. The duration of the Satya Yuga is therefore 4,800 \u00d7 360, or 1,728,000 years. The duration of the Tret\u0101 Yuga is 3,600 \u00d7 360, or 1,296,000 years. The duration of the Dv\u0101para Yuga is 2,400 \u00d7 360, or 864,000 years.<ref name=web>{{Cite book|url=http://vedabase.com/sb/3/11/19/|title=SB 3.11.19|first=|last=|access-date=15 July 2011|website=vedabase.com|date=2011-07-15}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nThe Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a Time measurement section of the Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a Book I Chapter III adds:\n\n* 2 Ayanas (6-month periods, see above) = 1 human year or 1 day of the devas.\n* 12,000 divine years = 4 Yugas (= 4,320,000 human years) = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga (also is equal to 12,000 Daiva [divine] Yuga).\n* 2 \u00d7 12,000 = 24,000 divine year = 12,000 revolutions of sun around its dual.\n\nWhile the long yuga count is the most popular, it does not correlate to any known celestial motion found in the [[Astronomical Almanac]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} The value of 24,000 years fits relatively close with the modern astronomical calculation of one full [[Axial precession (astronomy)#Effects|precession of the equinox]], which takes 25,772 years.{{efn|This phenomenon is observed as the stars moving retrograde across the sky at about 50 arc seconds per year, and is thought to produce periods of warm ages and ice ages known as the [[Milankovitch cycle]].}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Thus, the yuga cycle may have some basis in known terrestrial cycles. [[Srimad Bhagavatam]] 3.11.19 describes the timespans of the [[demigod|deva]]s, in which a year of a yuga is a year of the demigods. It is this second sloka which appears to have been modified over the years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Decline==\nThe descending ages see a gradual decline of dharma, wisdom, knowledge, intellectual capability, life span, emotional and physical strength.\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]'' \u2013  Virtue reigns supreme. Human stature was 21 cubits (33 ft 6 inches). Average human lifespan was 100,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]'' \u2013 There was 3 quarter virtue and 1 quarter sin. Normal human stature was 14 cubits (22 ft 4 inches). Average human lifespan was 10,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Dwapara Yuga]]'' \u2013 There was 1 half virtue and 1 half sin. Normal human stature was 7 cubits (11 ft 2 inches). Average human lifespan was 1,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]'' \u2013 There is 1 quarter virtue and 3 quarter sin. Normal human stature is 3.5 cubits (5 ft 3 inches). Average human lifespan will be 100 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nComparing the present to each Yuga's characteristics, one can know that we are living in ''Kali Yuga'', which is said to have started in 3102 BCE<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4DZYbWQbKAsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richter-Ushanas+indus+script+and+the+rgveda#v=onepage&q=yuga&f=false|title=The Indus Script and Rg-veda|page=16|first=Egbert|last=Richter-Ushanas|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|year=1997|isbn=9788120814059}}</ref> when [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]] left Earth to return to His eternal abode. (See [[Kali Yuga]]).{{efn|According to [[Sri Yukteswar Giri]], guru of [[Paramahansa Yogananda]],  The ascending  phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE (not exactly). Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri yukteswar,since nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te-ftAEACAAJ&dq=yukteswar+1949|title=The Holy Science|author=Swami Yukteswar|publisher=Yogoda Sat-Sanga Society of India|year=1949|page={{page needed|date=August 2018}}}}.</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ayanamsa]]\n* [[Hindu units of time]]\n* [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]].\n* [[Vedic-Puranic chronology]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system Vedic knowledge online, ''Vedic Time System '']\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n{{Legendary progenitors}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Theories of history]]\n[[Category:Time in Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Four Yugas| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{About||the 2006 '''film'''|Yuga (film)}}\n{{short description|Epoch or era in a four age cycle in Hinduism}}\n{{more citations needed|date=April 2018}}\n{{Hinduism small}}\n\n[[File:Four Yugas of Hindu Eschatology.svg|thumb|368x368px|The Four Yugas in one cycle according to some modern scholars, Hindu Cosmology]]\n\nA '''Yuga''' in [[Hinduism]] is an [[unit of time|epoch]] or [[era]]. There are a total of four Yugas: ''[[Satya Yuga]]'', ''[[Treta Yuga]],'' ''[[Dvapara Yuga]], and'' ''[[Kali Yuga]]''. The four Yugas differ in duration, virtues, etc. where Satya Yuga has the most, Treta Yuga the 2nd most, Dvapara the 3rd most, and Kali Yuga the least.\n\nA '''Mahayuga''' or '''Chaturyuga''' (also an epoch) is a cycle of the Yugas which can be followed by another Mahayuga of the same duration. Each Mahayuga consists of a descending set of the four Yugas where one Mahayuga ends with Kali Yuga and another starts with Satya Yuga (S,T,D,K) (S,T,D,K).\n\nSome modern scholars believe in a Mahayuga consisting of a much shorter descending and ascending set of the four Yugas where each Mahayuga starts and ends with Satya Yuga and has two Kali Yugas occuring in the middle (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S) (S,T,D,K,K,D,T,S). \n\nAccording to the epic [[Mahabharata]], the current age is Kali Yuga which started in 3102 BCE after [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]] left this world. (See [[Kali Yuga]]). Examining each yuga's characteristics, one can easily see that the current age is Kali Yuga.\n\nSome modern scholars say that our present time is ascending Kali Yuga,<ref>{{cite book| url = https://books.google.com/?id=BBwLVlOipyUC&pg=PA15&dq=four+yugas#v=onepage&q=four%20yugas&f=false| title=The Path to Immortality|page=15|first1= Mark L.|last1=Prophet|first2=Elizabeth|last2=Clare Prophet|author2-link=Elizabeth Clare Prophet|publisher= Summit University Press| isbn=9781932890099| year=2006}}</ref> while some other scholars say that Kali Yuga ended in 1700 CE and now we're in ascending Dwapara Yuga.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Holy Science|last=Swami|first=Sri Yukeshwar Giri|publisher=Yogoda Satsang Society|year=1949|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Characteristics of the four Yugas ==\nThere are four Yugas:\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]'' (or Krita Yuga)\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]''\n* ''[[Dwapara Yuga]]''\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]''\n\n=== Characteristics of each Yuga ===\n\n* '''Satya Yuga''' (\"The age of truth\" or \"[[Golden Age#Hindu|Golden Age]]\"): The first and best yuga. It was the age of truth and perfection. This yuga had no crimes and all humans were kind and friendly. The Krita Yuga was so named because there was but one religion, and all men were saintly: therefore they were not required to perform religious ceremonies. Humans were long lived, powerfully built, honest, youthful, vigorous, erudite and virtuous. The Vedas were one. All mankind could attain to supreme blessedness. There was no agriculture or mining as the earth yielded those riches on its own. Weather was pleasant and everyone was happy. There were no religious sects. There was no disease, decrepitude or fear of anything.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n* '''Treta Yuga''': This is the second yuga in order. However, \"treta\" means the \"third\". In this age, virtue diminishes slightly. At the beginning of the age, many emperors rise to dominance and conquer the world. Wars become frequent and weather begins to change to extremities. People become slightly diminished compared to their predecessors. Agriculture, labour and mining become existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n* '''Dvapara Yuga''': This is the third yuga in order. However, \"dvapara\" means \"two\". In this age, people become tainted with qualities and aren't as strong as their ancestors. Diseases become rampant. Humans are discontent and fight each other. Vedas are divided into four parts. People still possess characteristics of youth in old age. Average lifespan of humans is around a few centuries.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n* '''Kal Yuga''': The final age. It is the age of darkness and ignorance. People stop following [[Dharma]] and lack virtue. They become slaves to their passions and are barely as powerful as their earliest ancestors in the Satya Yuga. Society falls into disuse and people become liars and hypocrites. Knowledge is lost and scriptures are diminished. Humans eat forbidden and dirty food. The environment is polluted, water and food become scarce. Wealth is heavily diminished. Families become non-existent.{{Citation needed|date=April 2017}}\n\n==The Traditional cycle of Yugas==\n[[File:Time Units in Hindu Cosmology.png|frame|Relationship between various time units in Hindu cosmology]]\n\nThe traditional cycle of the Yugas has been mentioned in the [[Mahabharata]] and it is widely accepted since ancient times.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} The 4th century indian mathematician [[Aryabhata]] calculated the beginning of Kali Yuga.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nEach cycle of a Mahayuga repeats the four Yugas (ages) in the following order: Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali.<ref>{{Cite web|url=\nhttps://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/|title=\n\u015ar\u012bmad-Bh\u0101gavatam (Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a) 12.2.39 (yugas order)|website=Bhaktivedanta Vedabase|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>\n\n{{cquote|text=The cycle of four ages \u2014 Satya, Tret\u0101, Dv\u0101para and Kali \u2014 continues perpetually among living beings on this earth, repeating the same general sequence of events.|source=[https://vedabase.io/en/library/sb/12/2/39/ Bh\u0101gavata Pur\u0101\u1e47a 12.2.39]}}\n\n'''(For all the below numbers, see [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]]).'''\n\n* Satya Yuga\u20141,728,000 years (4800 divine)\n* Treta Yuga\u20141,296,000 years (3600 divine)\n* Dvapara Yuga\u2014864,000 years (2400 divine)\n* Kali Yuga\u2014432,000 years (1200 divine)\n\nWith one traditional Mahayuga cycle containing a set of descending yugas, it lasts for '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''. This differs greatly from the modern cycle's '''24,000 years'''.\n\nTo calculate the lifespan of the universe or Brahma using the Mahayuga duration, see the \"Current Date\" section of [[Hindu units of time]].\n\n==The Modern cycle of Yugas==\n\nA shorter calculation is promoted <ref>{{Citation|last=Sadhguru|title=The Great Cycles or 'YUGAS' Isha Fondation Sadhguru|date=2017-09-12|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eaHVNQwO68E|volume=|pages=|access-date=2019-04-12}}</ref> by modern day spiritual leaders such as [[Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri]] giving the approximate length of yugas as:\n\n* Satya Yuga\u20144800 years\n* Treta Yuga\u20143600 years\n* Dvapara Yuga\u20142400 years\n* Kali Yuga\u20141200 years\n\nWith one modern Mahayuga cycle containing a set of descending and ascending yugas{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}, it lasts for '''24,000 years'''. This differs greatly from the traditional cycle's '''4,320,000 years (12,000 divine years)'''.\n\nSome other scholars{{Who|date=April 2020}} believe in a 25,772 year cycle because it coincides with [[axial precession]], [[Astronomical precession]] and another planetary body ([[Planet Nine]]) that influences our solar system.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} {{Original research|date=February 2020}}\n\nThe common belief until Swami Sri Yukteswar Giri had analyzed the dating of the Yuga cycles was that the Kali Yuga would last for roughly 432,000 years after the end of the Dwapara Yuga (3102 BCE).{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} It's believed that this originated during the puranic times when the famous astronomer Aryabhatta recalculated the timeline by artificially inflating the traditional 12,000 year figure with a multiplication of 360, which was represented as the number of \"human years\" that make up a single \"divine year\".{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} It is believed that this was likely a purposeful miscalculation due to conflicts with one of the preeminent astronomer of the time [[Brahmagupta]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nHowever, both the Mahabharata (which was used by Aryabhatta in his calculations) and the Manu Smriti have the original value of 12,000 years for one half of the Yuga cycle.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nAccording to one Puranic astronomical estimate, the four Yuga have the following durations:<ref name=\"penprase182\" />\n\n*Satya Yuga equals 1,728,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=sm0BfUKwct0C&pg=PA50&lpg=PA50&dq=4,000+%2B+400+%2B+400+%3D+4,800+divine+years+(%3D+1,728,000+human+years)#v=onepage&q=4%2C000%20%2B%20400%20%2B%20400%20%3D%204%2C800%20divine%20years%20(%3D%201%2C728%2C000%20human%20years)&f=false|title=Tracing The Way: Spiritual Dimensions of the World Religions|page=50|first=Hans|last=Kng|publisher=A&C Black|isbn=9780826494238|date=2006-10-31}}</ref>\n*Treta Yuga equals 1,296,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Dvapara Yuga equals 864,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Kali Yuga equals 432,000 human years<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nTogether, these four yuga constitute one Mahayuga, equal to 4.32 million human years.<ref name=penprase182>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pQHNDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA137|title=The Power of Stars|publisher=Springer|page=182|first=Bryan E.|last=Penprase|isbn=9783319525976|date=2017-05-05}}</ref> According to one version, there are 1,000 Mahayugas in one day of [[Brahma]] or 4.32 billion human years. A Mahakalpa consists of 100 years of Brahma.<ref name=penprase182/>\n\nAccording to [[Srimad Bhagavatam]] 3.11.19, which most scholars agree was composed around Mahabharat war (3000 to 3100 BCE){{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}, the Yugas are much longer, using a divine year in which one day is equal to one human year, thus:\n\n{{cquote|one year of [[Deva (Hinduism)|divine beings]] is equal to 360 years of the human beings. The duration of the Satya Yuga is therefore 4,800 \u00d7 360, or 1,728,000 years. The duration of the Tret\u0101 Yuga is 3,600 \u00d7 360, or 1,296,000 years. The duration of the Dv\u0101para Yuga is 2,400 \u00d7 360, or 864,000 years.<ref name=web>{{Cite book|url=http://vedabase.com/sb/3/11/19/|title=SB 3.11.19|first=|last=|access-date=15 July 2011|website=vedabase.com|date=2011-07-15}}</ref>|sign=|source=}}\n\nThe Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a Time measurement section of the Vi\u1e63\u1e47u Pur\u0101\u1e47a Book I Chapter III adds:\n\n* 2 Ayanas (6-month periods, see above) = 1 human year or 1 day of the devas.\n* 12,000 divine years = 4 Yugas (= 4,320,000 human years) = 1 Mah\u0101-Yuga (also is equal to 12,000 Daiva [divine] Yuga).\n* 2 \u00d7 12,000 = 24,000 divine year = 12,000 revolutions of sun around its dual.\n\nWhile the long yuga count is the most popular, it does not correlate to any known celestial motion found in the [[Astronomical Almanac]].{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} The value of 24,000 years fits relatively close with the modern astronomical calculation of one full [[Axial precession (astronomy)#Effects|precession of the equinox]], which takes 25,772 years.{{efn|This phenomenon is observed as the stars moving retrograde across the sky at about 50 arc seconds per year, and is thought to produce periods of warm ages and ice ages known as the [[Milankovitch cycle]].}}{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Thus, the yuga cycle may have some basis in known terrestrial cycles. [[Srimad Bhagavatam]] 3.11.19 describes the timespans of the [[demigod|deva]]s, in which a year of a yuga is a year of the demigods. It is this second sloka which appears to have been modified over the years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Decline==\nThe descending ages see a gradual decline of dharma, wisdom, knowledge, intellectual capability, life span, emotional and physical strength.\n* ''[[Satya Yuga]]'' \u2013  Virtue reigns supreme. Human stature was 21 cubits (33 ft 6 inches). Average human lifespan was 100,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Treta Yuga]]'' \u2013 There was 3 quarter virtue and 1 quarter sin. Normal human stature was 14 cubits (22 ft 4 inches). Average human lifespan was 10,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Dwapara Yuga]]'' \u2013 There was 1 half virtue and 1 half sin. Normal human stature was 7 cubits (11 ft 2 inches). Average human lifespan was 1,000 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n* ''[[Kali Yuga]]'' \u2013 There is 1 quarter virtue and 3 quarter sin. Normal human stature is 3.5 cubits (5 ft 3 inches). Average human lifespan will be 100 years.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nComparing the present to each Yuga's characteristics, one can know that we are living in ''Kali Yuga'', which is said to have started in 3102 BCE<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=4DZYbWQbKAsC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Richter-Ushanas+indus+script+and+the+rgveda#v=onepage&q=yuga&f=false|title=The Indus Script and Rg-veda|page=16|first=Egbert|last=Richter-Ushanas|publisher=Motilal Banarsidass|year=1997|isbn=9788120814059}}</ref> when [[Krishna|Lord Krishna]] left Earth to return to His eternal abode. (See [[Kali Yuga]]).{{efn|According to [[Sri Yukteswar Giri]], guru of [[Paramahansa Yogananda]],  The ascending  phase of the Kali Yuga began in September 499 CE (not exactly). Since September 1699, we have been in the ascending phase of the Dwapara Yuga. According to Sri yukteswar,since nobody wanted to announce the bad news of the beginning of the descending Kali Yuga, so they kept adding years to the Dvapara date (at that time 2400 Dvapara) only retitling the epoch to Kali.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=Te-ftAEACAAJ&dq=yukteswar+1949|title=The Holy Science|author=Swami Yukteswar|publisher=Yogoda Sat-Sanga Society of India|year=1949|page={{page needed|date=August 2018}}}}.</ref>}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Ayanamsa]]\n* [[Hindu units of time]]\n* [[List of numbers in Hindu scriptures]].\n* [[Vedic-Puranic chronology]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://veda.wikidot.com/vedic-time-system Vedic knowledge online, ''Vedic Time System '']\n{{Time in religion and mythology}}\n{{Brahmanda}}\n{{Legendary progenitors}}\n\n[[Category:Hindu astronomy]]\n[[Category:Hindu philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Units of time]]\n[[Category:Theories of history]]\n[[Category:Time in Hinduism]]\n[[Category:Four Yugas| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jroberson108", "label": "safe", "comment": "Add superscript formatting.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Yuga"}
{"title_page": "Katherine Esp\u00edn", "text_new": "{{short description|Ecuadorian model and beauty queen}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Katherine Esp\u00edn\n| image        = MissEarth2016.jpg\n| birth_name   = Katherine Elizabeth Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1992|11|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Troncal Canton|La Troncal]], [[Ecuador]]\n| height       = {{height|m=1.70|precision=0}}\n| measurements = [[BWH|Bust]]: {{convert|89|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}<br />Waist: {{convert|60|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}<br />Hips: {{convert|93|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}\n| hair_color   = Black\n| eye_color    = Black\n| title        = {{Plainlist|\n* Miss Bikini Ecuador 2015\n* [[Miss Earth Ecuador]] 2016\n* [[Miss Earth 2016]]\n}}\n| competitions  = [[Miss Earth 2016]]<br>(Winner)\n}}\n\n'''Katherine Elizabeth Esp\u00edn''' (born 15 November 1992) is an [[Ecuadorians|Ecuadorian]] [[model (profession)|model]] and [[beauty queen]] who was appointed as [[Miss Earth Ecuador|Miss Earth Ecuador 2016]].<ref name=\"MEEcuador1\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez crowned as Miss Earth Ecuador 2016|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/Katherine-Espn-Gmez-crowned-as-Miss-Earth-Ecuador-2016/articleshow/53650814.cms|accessdate=13 August 2016|agency=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=indiatimes.com|date=11 August 2016}}</ref> She is best known as the winner of the [[Miss Earth 2016]] pageant,<ref name=\"ME2016A\">{{cite news|last1=Adina|first1=Armin P.|title=Ecuador wins 2016 Miss Earth pageant|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/242252/242252/|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|publisher=lifestyle.inquirer.net|date= 29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016B\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Miss Earth 2016: Miss Ecuador wins beauty pageant; crowning ceremony in photos|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/miss-earth-2016-live-winner-photos-701813|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[International Business Times]]|publisher=ibtimes.co.in|date= 29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016C\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Who is Finest Of Them All? Choose Your Favorite Contestant for Miss Earth-2016|url=https://sputniknews.com/society/201610301046897295-favorite-miss-earth-contestant-2016/|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]]|date=30 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016D\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Ecuatoriana Katherine Esp\u00edn gan\u00f3 el Miss Earth 2016 en Filipinas|url=http://m.eluniverso.com/vida-estilo/2016/10/29/nota/5880370/ecuatoriana-gano-miss-earth-2016-filipinas|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[El Universo]]|date=29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016E\">{{cite news|last=Heyer|first=Daisy|title=Ecuador wint Miss Earth, Nederland grijpt mis|url=http://m.metronieuws.nl/xl/babes/2016/10/ecuador-wint-miss-earth-nederland-grijpt-mis|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[Metro (Dutch newspaper)|Metro]]|date=30 October 2016}}</ref> making her the second [[Miss Earth]] winner from Ecuador next to [[Olga \u00c1lava]] who won the crown in [[Miss Earth 2011|2011]].<ref name=\"ME2016D\" /><ref name=\"2ndCrown1\">{{cite news|last=Concepcion|first=Eton B.|title=It's take 2 for Ecuador in Miss Earth|url=http://thestandard.com.ph/showbitz/220332/it-s-take-2-for-ecuador-in-miss-earth.html|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[The Standard (Philippines)|The Standard]]|date=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2ndCrown2\">{{cite news|last=Dumaual|first=Mario|title=Miss Earth 2016 denies undergoing plastic surgery|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/life/11/01/16/miss-earth-2016-denies-undergoing-plastic-surgery|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[ABS-CBN News Channel|ABS-CBN News]]|date=1 November 2016}}</ref> She is also the National Director of Miss Earth Ecuador pageant at present.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn Becomes National Director of Miss Earth Ecuador|url=https://tkop.org/2018/02/06/katherine-espin-appointed-national-director-of-miss-earth-ecuador/|website=The Kaleidoscope of Pageantry|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nAs published in Miss Earth's official website, Espin described her childhood days as the following:\n\n{{quote|When I was 9 years old I traveled to [[United States]] to study and live with my parents who were working there. I finished elementary and high school in [[New York City]], I lived there for 6 and a half years. During my school years I was able to get many academic achievements such as student of the month, principals honor roll, science fair awards during 4 years, art awards in a competition in New York state. I also had sports awards and among them was track race winner. Due to my parent's occupation I couldn't spent much time with them so I had to learn to be very independent since I was 11 years old, for example I had to travel by train to go to school by myself, stay home alone and learn how to cook because my parents were always working. All those experiences made me a strong independent woman and I thank my parents for that. It wasn't easy but we made it possible together as a family. I had an amazing childhood life but lonely for 13 years because I was a single child until my sister was born when I was 13. I had facial paralysis when I was 13 and had to struggle with that for a while during my childhood.}}\n\n==Pageantry==\nPrior to competing in the Miss Earth pageant, Espin represented Ecuador but did not win at the [[Reinado Internacional del Caf\u00e9 2013]], but she emerged first runner in the Miss Bikini Universe 2015.<ref name=\"MBU2015\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn es Miss Bikini Universe Ecuador|url=http://www.elmercurio.com.ec/488181-katherine-espin-es-miss-bikini-universe-ecuador/#.WBTMEfl96Uk|accessdate=30 July 2015|agency=[[El Mercurio (Ecuador)|El Mercurio]]|publisher=|date=22 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/Katherine-Espn-Gmez-crowned-as-Miss-Earth-Ecuador-2016/articleshow/53650814.cms|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez crowned as Miss Earth Ecuador 2016|last=News|first=Times of India|date=11 August 2016|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Earth 2016===\nEspin represented Ecuador in Miss Earth 2016 and competed with 82 other delegates from around the world. During the pre-pageant events, she won gold medal at the press presentation as part of the \"Darling of the Press\" award and tied up with [[Miss Philippines Earth|the Philippines']] bet, [[Imelda Schweighart]].<ref name=\"Press1\">{{cite news|last1=Caparas|first1=Celso de Guzman|title=Miss Earth's Darlings of the Press|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2016/10/22/1635972/miss-earths-darlings-press|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Star]]|publisher=philstar.com|date=22 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Press2\">{{cite news|last1=Requintina|first1=Robert R.|title=Ecuador beauty leads in 2016 Miss Earth pre-pageant activities|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/ecuador-beauty-leads-in-2016-miss-earth-pre-pageant-activities/|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[Manila Bulletin]]|publisher=mb.com.ph|date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Press3\">{{cite news|last1=Pata|first1=Danny|title=PHL, Ecuador bets tie for 'darling of the press' at Miss Earth media event|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/584596/lifestyle/phl-ecuador-bets-tie-for-darling-of-the-press-at-miss-earth-media-event|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[GMA Network]]|publisher=gmanetwork.com|date=11 October 2016}}</ref> As the pre-pageant activities continued, she garnered more medals: gold medals for the resort's wear and long gown competitions; silver medals for the swimsuit competition; bronze medal for the national costume competition. Aside from getting several medals, Espin was able to get awards from various sponsors as well. At the end of the pageant, Espin won Miss Earth 2016.<ref name=\"ME2016F\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Ecuador is Miss Earth 2016|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2016/10/29/1638729/ecuador-miss-earth-2016|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Star]]|publisher=philstar.com|date= October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016G\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Full list: Winners of Miss Earth 2016|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/full-list-winners-miss-earth-2016/293808/|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Manila Times]]|publisher=manilatimes.net|date= October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the media, she stated that she had been wanting to be Miss Earth since she was 16 years old and she further stated that to reporters, \"''There was an Ecuadorian named Olga Alava, [who] won the pageant, and I remembered that when I saw her, I saw myself winning and I'm making my dream come true''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/specials/miss-earth/150355-katherine-espin-miss-earth-2016-ecuador|title=Ecuador's Katherine Esp\u00edn on her Miss Earth 2016 win|last=Villano|first=Alexa|date=30 October 2016|work=[[Rappler]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Miss Earth reign==\nEspin and Miss Earth Air 2016 [[Michelle Gomez]] travelled to [[Reunion Island]] for the coronation of [[Miss Earth Reunion|Miss Earth Reunion 2017]], and conducted environmental education campaign at Charles Cros -Mont Ver Les Hauts School where they planted trees with the students, and visited eco-tourism spots including the island's electric car company, [[Renault]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/278135/miss-earth-2016-kath-espin-stay/|title=Miss Earth 2016 Kath Espin is here to stay|last=Lejano|first=Don|date=7 November 2017|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Espin flew to [[Angola]] for the [[Earth Day|Earth Day 2017]] where she crowned Miss Earth Angola 2017 and graced a tree planting activity together with Fundacao Verde which was supported by the Government of Angola and the Ministerio do Ambiente.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/emerlinda-martins-crowned-miss-earth-angola-2017/articleshow/58357155.cms|title=Emerlinda Martins crowned Miss Earth Angola 2017|last=News|first=Angola|date=25 April 2017|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missearth.tv/news.php|title=Katherine Espin Celebrating Earth Day in Angola|last=News|first=Miss Earth|date=24 April 2017|website=Miss Earth|archive-date=27 November 2017}}</ref> On the same month, Espin  graced the launch of Miss Earth Ghana Organization's \"''Trash in Bin Campaign''\" in [[Ghana]] with Miss Earth Ghana 2016 Deborah Eyram Dodor, aims to encourage everyone in Ghana to practice proper waste disposal and segregation.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\nEspin attended the red carpet of [[Philippine President]] [[Rodrigo Duterte]]'s [[State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|State of the Nation Address]] (SONA) at the [[Batasang Pambansa Complex]] on July 24, 2017. She joined [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]] vice governor Tonypet Albano.<ref name=\"Duterte-sona\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Miss Earth 2016 attends SONA 2017|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/life/07/24/17/miss-earth-2016-attends-sona-2017|accessdate=24 July 2017|agency=[[ABS-CBN]]|publisher=[[ABS-CBNnews.com]]|date= 24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Espin travelled in [[Singapore]] as an honorary member along with thirty-three delegates from the League of Vice Governors of the Philippines to attended the foreign study \"''Driving Excellence in Governance''\" at the [[National University of Singapore]]'s Lee Kuan Yew School of Public Policy (NUS-LKYSPP), which is the academic phase project funded under the General Appropriations Act, was overseen by the Development Academy of the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dap.edu.ph/33-philippine-vice-governors-officials-attend-singapore-study/|title=33 Philippine vice governors, officials attend Singapore study|last=News|first=Development Academy of the Philippines|date=1 August  2017|website=Development Academy of the Philippines|archive-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe travelled to [[Puerto Rico]] in August 2017 to attend the coronation of Karla Victoria Aponte Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/beauty-pageants/foreign-pageants/karla-victoria-aponte-will-represent-puerto-rico-at-miss-earth-2017/videoshow/59883197.cms|title=Karla Victoria Aponte will represent Puerto Rico at Miss Earth 2017|last=News|first=Puerto Rico|date=2 August 2017|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, she went to [[Chile]] and graced the activities of the contest, [[Nuestra Belleza Chile|Nuestra Belleza Chile 2017]] (Miss Earth Chile 2017) and served as the chairwoman of the board of judges of the pageant which was won by Sof\u00eda Manzur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=http://web.observador.cl/la-calerana-sofia-manzur-fue-coronada-como-la-miss-earth-chile-2017/&prev=search|title=La calerana Sof\u00eda Manzur fue coronada como la \u201cMiss Earth Chile 2017\u201d|last=News|first=Chile|date=3 September 2017|work=Diario El Observador|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=https://www.guioteca.com/belleza/miss-earth-chile-2017-corona-a-sofia-manzur-como-nueva-reina-de-belleza-fotos-de-la-ganadora/&prev=search|title=Miss Earth Chile 2017 corona a Sof\u00eda Manzur como nueva reina de belleza: Fotos de la ganadora|last=Sarasqueta|first=Alejandra|date=4 September 2017|work=Guioteca|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her reign, she has traveled to [[Angola]], [[Reunion Island]], [[Singapore]], [[United States]], [[Middle East]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Chile]] and numerous trips around the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/specials/miss-earth/185366-katherine-espin-miss-earth-2016-reign-activities|title=Katherine Espin on her reign as Miss Earth 2016|last=Villano|first=Alexa|date=16 October 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4EplKVzTmVU Miss Earth Ecuador 2016 Eco-Beauty Video]\n* [http://www.missearth.tv/missearthecuador.php Katherine Espin  at Miss Earth Official Website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before={{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Angelia Ong]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth]]\n|years=[[Miss Earth 2016|2016]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Karen Ibasco]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[\u00c1ngela Bonilla]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Earth Ecuador]]\n|years=2016}}\n{{S-aft|after=Lessie Giler}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Miss Earth 2016 delegates}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders 2016}}\n{{Miss Earth titleholders}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Espin, Katherine}}\n[[Category:1992 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Miss World Ecuador]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth 2016 contestants]]\n[[Category:Ecuadorian beauty pageant winners]]\n[[Category:Ecuadorian female models]]\n[[Category:Ecuadorian people of Spanish descent]]\n[[Category:People from La Troncal Canton]]\n[[Category:Ecuadorian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Miss Earth winners]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ecuadorian model and beauty queen}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name         = Katherine Esp\u00edn\n| image        = MissEarth2016.jpg\n| birth_name   = Katherine Elizabeth Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1992|11|15|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[La Troncal Canton|La Troncal]], [[Ecuador]]\n| height       = {{height|m=1.70|precision=0}}\n| measurements = [[BWH|Bust]]: {{convert|89|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}<br />Waist: {{convert|60|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}<br />Hips: {{convert|93|cm|in|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}\n| hair_color   = Black\n| eye_color    = Black\n| title        = {{Plainlist|\n* Miss Bikini Ecuador 2015\n* [[Miss Earth Ecuador]] 2016\n* [[Miss Earth 2016]]\n}}\n| competitions  = [[Miss Earth 2016]]<br>(Winner)\n}}\n\n'''Katherine Elizabeth Esp\u00edn''' (born 15 November 1992) is an [[Ecuadorians|Ecuadorian]] [[model (profession)|model]] and [[beauty queen]] who was appointed as [[Miss Earth Ecuador|Miss Earth Ecuador 2016]].<ref name=\"MEEcuador1\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez crowned as Miss Earth Ecuador 2016|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/Katherine-Espn-Gmez-crowned-as-Miss-Earth-Ecuador-2016/articleshow/53650814.cms|accessdate=13 August 2016|agency=[[The Times of India]]|publisher=indiatimes.com|date=11 August 2016}}</ref> She is best known as the winner of the [[Miss Earth 2016]] pageant,<ref name=\"ME2016A\">{{cite news|last1=Adina|first1=Armin P.|title=Ecuador wins 2016 Miss Earth pageant|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/242252/242252/|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|publisher=lifestyle.inquirer.net|date= 29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016B\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Miss Earth 2016: Miss Ecuador wins beauty pageant; crowning ceremony in photos|url=http://www.ibtimes.co.in/miss-earth-2016-live-winner-photos-701813|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[International Business Times]]|publisher=ibtimes.co.in|date= 29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016C\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Who is Finest Of Them All? Choose Your Favorite Contestant for Miss Earth-2016|url=https://sputniknews.com/society/201610301046897295-favorite-miss-earth-contestant-2016/|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[Sputnik (news agency)|Sputnik]]|date=30 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016D\">{{cite news|last=|first=|title=Ecuatoriana Katherine Esp\u00edn gan\u00f3 el Miss Earth 2016 en Filipinas|url=http://m.eluniverso.com/vida-estilo/2016/10/29/nota/5880370/ecuatoriana-gano-miss-earth-2016-filipinas|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[El Universo]]|date=29 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016E\">{{cite news|last=Heyer|first=Daisy|title=Ecuador wint Miss Earth, Nederland grijpt mis|url=http://m.metronieuws.nl/xl/babes/2016/10/ecuador-wint-miss-earth-nederland-grijpt-mis|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[Metro (Dutch newspaper)|Metro]]|date=30 October 2016}}</ref> making her the second [[Miss Earth]] winner from Ecuador next to [[Olga \u00c1lava]] who won the crown in [[Miss Earth 2011|2011]].<ref name=\"ME2016D\" /><ref name=\"2ndCrown1\">{{cite news|last=Concepcion|first=Eton B.|title=It's take 2 for Ecuador in Miss Earth|url=http://thestandard.com.ph/showbitz/220332/it-s-take-2-for-ecuador-in-miss-earth.html|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[The Standard (Philippines)|The Standard]]|date=1 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"2ndCrown2\">{{cite news|last=Dumaual|first=Mario|title=Miss Earth 2016 denies undergoing plastic surgery|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/life/11/01/16/miss-earth-2016-denies-undergoing-plastic-surgery|accessdate=2 November 2016|newspaper=[[ABS-CBN News Channel|ABS-CBN News]]|date=1 November 2016}}</ref> She is also the National Director of Miss Earth Ecuador pageant at present.<ref>{{cite web|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn Becomes National Director of Miss Earth Ecuador|url=https://tkop.org/2018/02/06/katherine-espin-appointed-national-director-of-miss-earth-ecuador/|website=The Kaleidoscope of Pageantry|accessdate=6 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nAs published in Miss Earth's official website, Espin described her childhood days as the following:\n\n{{quote|When I was 9 years old I traveled to [[United States]] to study and live with my parents who were working there. I finished elementary and high school in [[New York City]], I lived there for 6 and a half years. During my school years I was able to get many academic achievements such as student of the month, principals honor roll, science fair awards during 4 years, art awards in a competition in New York state. I also had sports awards and among them was track race winner. Due to my parent's occupation I couldn't spent much time with them so I had to learn to be very independent since I was 11 years old, for example I had to travel by train to go to school by myself, stay home alone and learn how to cook because my parents were always working. All those experiences made me a strong independent woman and I thank my parents for that. It wasn't easy but we made it possible together as a family. I had an amazing childhood life but lonely for 13 years because I was a single child until my sister was born when I was 13. I had facial paralysis when I was 13 and had to struggle with that for a while during my childhood.}}\n\n==Pageantry==\nPrior to competing in the Miss Earth pageant, Espin represented Ecuador but did not win at the [[Reinado Internacional del Caf\u00e9 2013]], but she emerged first runner in the Miss Bikini Universe 2015.<ref name=\"MBU2015\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn es Miss Bikini Universe Ecuador|url=http://www.elmercurio.com.ec/488181-katherine-espin-es-miss-bikini-universe-ecuador/#.WBTMEfl96Uk|accessdate=30 July 2015|agency=[[El Mercurio (Ecuador)|El Mercurio]]|publisher=|date=22 July 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/Katherine-Espn-Gmez-crowned-as-Miss-Earth-Ecuador-2016/articleshow/53650814.cms|title=Katherine Esp\u00edn G\u00f3mez crowned as Miss Earth Ecuador 2016|last=News|first=Times of India|date=11 August 2016|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Miss Earth 2016===\nEspin represented Ecuador in Miss Earth 2016 and competed with 82 other delegates from around the world. During the pre-pageant events, she won gold medal at the press presentation as part of the \"Darling of the Press\" award and tied up with [[Miss Philippines Earth|the Philippines']] bet, [[Imelda Schweighart]].<ref name=\"Press1\">{{cite news|last1=Caparas|first1=Celso de Guzman|title=Miss Earth's Darlings of the Press|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2016/10/22/1635972/miss-earths-darlings-press|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Star]]|publisher=philstar.com|date=22 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Press2\">{{cite news|last1=Requintina|first1=Robert R.|title=Ecuador beauty leads in 2016 Miss Earth pre-pageant activities|url=http://www.mb.com.ph/ecuador-beauty-leads-in-2016-miss-earth-pre-pageant-activities/|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[Manila Bulletin]]|publisher=mb.com.ph|date=16 October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Press3\">{{cite news|last1=Pata|first1=Danny|title=PHL, Ecuador bets tie for 'darling of the press' at Miss Earth media event|url=http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/584596/lifestyle/phl-ecuador-bets-tie-for-darling-of-the-press-at-miss-earth-media-event|accessdate=23 October 2016|agency=[[GMA Network]]|publisher=gmanetwork.com|date=11 October 2016}}</ref> As the pre-pageant activities continued, she garnered more medals: gold medals for the resort's wear and long gown competitions; silver medals for the swimsuit competition; bronze medal for the national costume competition. Aside from getting several medals, Espin was able to get awards from various sponsors as well. At the end of the pageant, Espin won Miss Earth 2016.<ref name=\"ME2016F\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Ecuador is Miss Earth 2016|url=http://www.philstar.com/entertainment/2016/10/29/1638729/ecuador-miss-earth-2016|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Philippine Star]]|publisher=philstar.com|date= October 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"ME2016G\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Full list: Winners of Miss Earth 2016|url=http://www.manilatimes.net/full-list-winners-miss-earth-2016/293808/|accessdate= 30 October 2016|agency=[[Manila Times]]|publisher=manilatimes.net|date= October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview with the media, she stated that she had been wanting to be Miss Earth since she was 16 years old and she further stated that to reporters, \"''There was an Ecuadorian named Olga Alava, [who] won the pageant, and I remembered that when I saw her, I saw myself winning and I'm making my dream come true''.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/specials/miss-earth/150355-katherine-espin-miss-earth-2016-ecuador|title=Ecuador's Katherine Esp\u00edn on her Miss Earth 2016 win|last=Villano|first=Alexa|date=30 October 2016|work=[[Rappler]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Miss Earth reign==\nEspin and Miss Earth Air 2016 [[Michelle Gomez]] travelled to [[Reunion Island]] for the coronation of [[Miss Earth Reunion|Miss Earth Reunion 2017]], and conducted environmental education campaign at Charles Cros -Mont Ver Les Hauts School where they planted trees with the students, and visited eco-tourism spots including the island's electric car company, [[Renault]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://lifestyle.inquirer.net/278135/miss-earth-2016-kath-espin-stay/|title=Miss Earth 2016 Kath Espin is here to stay|last=Lejano|first=Don|date=7 November 2017|work=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Espin flew to [[Angola]] for the [[Earth Day|Earth Day 2017]] where she crowned Miss Earth Angola 2017 and graced a tree planting activity together with Fundacao Verde which was supported by the Government of Angola and the Ministerio do Ambiente.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://beautypageants.indiatimes.com/miss-earth/emerlinda-martins-crowned-miss-earth-angola-2017/articleshow/58357155.cms|title=Emerlinda Martins crowned Miss Earth Angola 2017|last=News|first=Angola|date=25 April 2017|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.missearth.tv/news.php|title=Katherine Espin Celebrating Earth Day in Angola|last=News|first=Miss Earth|date=24 April 2017|website=Miss Earth|archive-date=27 November 2017}}</ref> On the same month, Espin  graced the launch of Miss Earth Ghana Organization's \"''Trash in Bin Campaign''\" in [[Ghana]] with Miss Earth Ghana 2016 Deborah Eyram Dodor, aims to encourage everyone in Ghana to practice proper waste disposal and segregation.{{cn|date=June 2018}}\n\nEspin attended the red carpet of [[Philippine President]] [[Rodrigo Duterte]]'s [[State of the Nation Address (Philippines)|State of the Nation Address]] (SONA) at the [[Batasang Pambansa Complex]] on July 24, 2017. She joined [[Isabela (province)|Isabela]] vice governor Tonypet Albano.<ref name=\"Duterte-sona\">{{cite news|last1=|first1=|title=Miss Earth 2016 attends SONA 2017|url=http://news.abs-cbn.com/life/07/24/17/miss-earth-2016-attends-sona-2017|accessdate=24 July 2017|agency=[[ABS-CBN]]|publisher=[[ABS-CBNnews.com]]|date= 24 July 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2017, Espin travelled in [[Singapore]] as an honorary member along with thirty-three delegates from the League of Vice Governors of the Philippines to attended the foreign study \"''Driving Excellence in Governance''\" at the [[National University of Singapore]]'s Lee Kuan Yew School of Public Policy (NUS-LKYSPP), which is the academic phase project funded under the General Appropriations Act, was overseen by the Development Academy of the Philippines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dap.edu.ph/33-philippine-vice-governors-officials-attend-singapore-study/|title=33 Philippine vice governors, officials attend Singapore study|last=News|first=Development Academy of the Philippines|date=1 August  2017|website=Development Academy of the Philippines|archive-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nShe travelled to [[Puerto Rico]] in August 2017 to attend the coronation of Karla Victoria Aponte Miss Earth Puerto Rico 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/videos/beauty-pageants/foreign-pageants/karla-victoria-aponte-will-represent-puerto-rico-at-miss-earth-2017/videoshow/59883197.cms|title=Karla Victoria Aponte will represent Puerto Rico at Miss Earth 2017|last=News|first=Puerto Rico|date=2 August 2017|work=[[The Times of India]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2017, she went to [[Chile]] and graced the activities of the contest, [[Nuestra Belleza Chile|Nuestra Belleza Chile 2017]] (Miss Earth Chile 2017) and served as the chairwoman of the board of judges of the pageant which was won by Sof\u00eda Manzur.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=http://web.observador.cl/la-calerana-sofia-manzur-fue-coronada-como-la-miss-earth-chile-2017/&prev=search|title=La calerana Sof\u00eda Manzur fue coronada como la \u201cMiss Earth Chile 2017\u201d|last=News|first=Chile|date=3 September 2017|work=Diario El Observador|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=es&u=https://www.guioteca.com/belleza/miss-earth-chile-2017-corona-a-sofia-manzur-como-nueva-reina-de-belleza-fotos-de-la-ganadora/&prev=search|title=Miss Earth Chile 2017 corona a Sof\u00eda Manzur como nueva reina de belleza: Fotos de la ganadora|last=Sarasqueta|first=Alejandra|date=4 September 2017|work=Guioteca|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nDuring her reign, she has traveled to [[Angola]], [[Reunion Island]], [[Singapore]], [[United States]], [[Middle East]], [[Puerto Rico]], [[Chile]] and numerous trips around the [[Philippines]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.rappler.com/life-and-style/specials/miss-earth/185366-katherine-espin-miss-earth-2016-reign-activities|title=Katherine Espin on her reign as Miss Earth 2016|last=Villano|first=Alexa|date=16 October 2017|work=[[Rappler]]|access-date=27 November 2017}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4EplKVzTmVU Miss Earth Ecuador 2016 Eco-Beauty Video]\n*[http://www.missearth.tv/missearthecuador.php Katherine Espin  at Miss Earth Official Website]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-ach}}\n{{S-bef|before={{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Angelia Ong]]